          "content": "## Pros and Cons Analysis for Review Approaches\n\nLet me break down the different approaches for reviewing artifacts and decisions from other angles:\n\n### **Approach 1: LLM-Based Multi-Perspective Reviews**\n\n**How it works**: Use external LLM tools with different system prompts to review phase artifacts from various professional perspectives.\n\n**Pros:**\n- **Rich, contextual feedback**: LLMs can provide detailed, nuanced reviews\n- **Multiple perspectives**: Can simulate architect, security expert, user experience, maintainability views\n- **Adaptive**: Can adjust review depth based on project complexity\n- **Natural language feedback**: Easy for users to understand and act on\n\n**Cons:**\n- **Dependency on external tools**: Requires LLM interaction tools to be available in MCP ecosystem\n- **Cost/performance**: Multiple LLM calls could be expensive or slow\n- **Consistency**: LLM reviews might vary in quality or focus\n- **False positives**: Might flag non-issues or miss subtle problems\n\n### **Approach 2: Workflow-Defined Review Checklists**\n\n**How it works**: Pre-defined review criteria and questions embedded in workflow YAML files.\n\n**Pros:**\n- **Predictable and consistent**: Same review criteria every time\n- **Fast execution**: No external API calls needed\n- **Customizable per workflow**: Different workflows can have different review focuses\n- **Educational**: Helps users learn what to look for in each phase\n\n**Cons:**\n- **Static nature**: Can't adapt to specific project contexts\n- **Limited depth**: Checklist-style reviews might miss complex issues\n- **Maintenance overhead**: Review criteria need to be kept up-to-date\n- **Less engaging**: Might feel mechanical compared to narrative feedback\n\n### **Approach 3: Hybrid Approach**\n\n**How it works**: Combine both LLM reviews and workflow-defined checklists.\n\n**Pros:**\n- **Best of both worlds**: Consistent baseline + adaptive insights\n- **Fallback mechanism**: If LLM tools unavailable, still have checklist reviews\n- **Layered validation**: Multiple validation layers increase quality\n- **User choice**: Users can choose which type of review they prefer\n\n**Cons:**\n- **Complexity**: More complex to implement and maintain\n- **Potential redundancy**: Reviews might overlap or contradict\n- **Configuration overhead**: More settings for users to manage\n\n## Artifacts and Decisions by Phase\n\nLet me define what would be reviewed in each phase:\n\n**Explore Phase Artifacts:**\n- Requirements understanding\n- Problem space analysis\n- Technology/approach research\n- Scope definition decisions\n- Risk identification\n\n**Plan Phase Artifacts:**\n- Implementation strategy\n- Task breakdown\n- Architecture decisions\n- Dependency analysis\n- Timeline estimates\n\n**Code Phase Artifacts:**\n- Code quality and structure\n- Test coverage\n- Error handling\n- Performance considerations\n- Security implementation\n\n**Commit Phase Artifacts:**\n- Documentation completeness\n- Deployment readiness\n- Code review compliance\n- Final testing results\n\n## User Preference Design Options\n\n### **Option A: Global User Preference**\n```json\n{\n  \"reviews\": {\n    \"enabled\": true,\n    \"type\": \"llm\", // \"checklist\", \"hybrid\", \"llm\"\n    \"perspectives\": [\"security\", \"architecture\", \"ux\"]\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### **Option B: Per-Workflow Configuration**\n```yaml\n# In workflow YAML\nreview_config:\n  default_enabled: false\n  available_types: [\"llm\", \"checklist\"]\n  perspectives:\n    - security\n    - architecture\n```\n\n### **Option C: Runtime User Choice**\nWhen `proceed_to_phase` is called, ask user: \"Would you like to conduct a review before proceeding to [next phase]?\"\n\n## My Recommendation\n\nI'm leaning toward **Approach 3 (Hybrid)** with **Option C (Runtime Choice)** because:\n\n1. **Flexibility**: Users can choose what works best for their current situation\n2. **Progressive enhancement**: Works without LLM tools, better with them\n3. **Learning opportunity**: Users can see both structured checklists and adaptive feedback\n4. **Non-intrusive**: Optional at runtime, doesn't require upfront configuration\n\n**Questions to help decide:**\n\n1. **User workflow preference**: Do you envision users typically wanting reviews, or only occasionally?\n\n2. **Review timing**: Should reviews happen:\n   - Automatically when `proceed_to_phase` is called?\n   - Via a separate `conduct_review` tool?\n   - As a prompt/question to the user?\n\n3. **Review scope**: Should reviews be:\n   - Phase-specific (only review current phase artifacts)?\n   - Cumulative (review all progress so far)?\n   - Configurable per review?\n\nWhat's your intuition on these trade-offs? Do any of these approaches resonate with how you imagine users would want to interact with the review system?",
